    {
        "content": "<p>This is something I am interested in seeing in the library and it is nice someone has the bandwidth to tackle it. I think one could make contact with Inventiones level math pretty quickly here. </p>\n<p>Some comments:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Nothing said mentioned <code>n</code>which to me is the most important piece of information </li>\n<li>In my limited thought experiments, I don't see anything better than an custom inductive, along the lines of what limitsClosure is doing</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 573283553,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770815970
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The definition of strong generator mentions <code>n</code>. The individual closure operators listed don't, of course.</p>",
        "id": 573284134,
        "sender_full_name": "Justus Springer",
        "timestamp": 1770816118
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, my motivation is actually to make contact with <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.4007/annals.2021.193.3.1\">Annals level math</a> :)</p>",
        "id": 573284507,
        "sender_full_name": "Justus Springer",
        "timestamp": 1770816210
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That is much further away but a very good goal.</p>",
        "id": 573284617,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770816236
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know of a reasonable definition of a classical generator (in general, in this flavor) that doesn't go through n-step generation</p>",
        "id": 573284928,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770816309
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another good target (given the requisite geometry) is <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0021782423000612\">https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0021782423000612</a></p>",
        "id": 573285225,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770816378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I assume we want GAGA</p>",
        "id": 573285492,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770816433
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Other comments:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>thick is indeed the \"standard\" terminology but I can imagine versions where you don't want to impose this on each step</li>\n<li>similarly Neeman (in the referenced paper) constrains the shifts allowed </li>\n<li>I don't think there is any world we don't want it closed under isomorphisms </li>\n<li>the above suggests having a very flexible definition that can be specialized to the usual definition of nth level</li>\n<li>I think we already have the Karoubi closure as a reference point</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 573290418,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770817617
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ideally I would like <code>decide</code> to work ;)</p>",
        "id": 573290597,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770817660
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You will of course want the \"big\" version where you use coproducts of a given size, beyond finite. </p>\n<p>I am not sure of the value of closure under other colimit shapes generally in this setting. I am not sure anyone has really thought about it. Certainly it is something you want more generally though.</p>",
        "id": 573293509,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770818366
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it would be nice to have these constructions. (For triangulated categories, I believe that the only (co)limits which are relevant are coproducts and products.)<br>\nOn a related topic, at some point, I will upstream definitions about left/right localizing triangulated subcategories.</p>",
        "id": 573299539,
        "sender_full_name": "Joël Riou",
        "timestamp": 1770819757
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, you don't get a lot for free in a general triangulated category</p>",
        "id": 573299919,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1770819856
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just opened <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/35497\">#35497</a>, which defines the extension product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi><mo>⋆</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{A} \\star \\mathcal{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> of two object properties in a triangulated category and proves associativity.</p>",
        "id": 574548380,
        "sender_full_name": "Justus Springer",
        "timestamp": 1771431367
    }
]